'''Scot Eugene Brantley''' (born February 24, 1958) is an [[United States|American]] radio and television sports [[broadcaster]] and former college and professional [[American football|football]] player who was a [[linebacker]] in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) for eight seasons in the 1980s.  Brantley played [[college football]] for the [[University of Florida]], and thereafter, he played professionally for the [[Tampa Buccaneers]] of the NFL.

== Early years ==

Brantley was born in [[Chester, South Carolina]] in 1958.<ref name=pfbrprofile>Pro-Football-Reference.com, Players, [http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BranSc20.htm  Scot Brantley].  Retrieved July 1, 2010.</ref>  He attended [[Forest High School (Florida)|Forest High School]] in [[Ocala, Florida]],<ref name=dbfbprofile>databaseFootball.com, Players, [http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=BRANTSCO01  Scot Brantley].  Retrieved June 1, 2010.</ref> where he played [[high school football]] for the Forest Wildcats.  Brantley was a starting linebacker on the Wildcats [[varsity]] as a [[freshman]],<ref>Greg Larson, "[http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=iAUkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cgUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3089,2732417&dq=scot-brantley&hl=en  Wildcat Frosh Starts At Linebacker: Brantley Will Never See Jayvees]," ''Ocala Star-Banner'', p. 2B (October 12, 1972).  Retrieved July 1, 2010.</ref> and as a junior and senior, he was a member of the Wildcats' 1974 and 1975 Florida 3A high school state championship teams.  Brantley was twice named a high school [[All-American]] by ''[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]'' magazine, and was one of the mostly highly sought-after college recruits in the country in 1975.  He was also a standout [[outfielder]] for the Wildcats [[baseball]] team, and was drafted by the [[New York Mets]] despite having signed with the [[Florida Gators]] to play college football.<ref>Jim Smith, "[http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Dz8xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jAUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3488,1832669&dq=scot-brantley&hl=en  Boston, Auburn: Forest's Nichols In Driver's Seat]," ''Ocala Star-banner'', p. D1 (June 9, 1976).  Retrieved July 1, 2010.</ref>

== College career ==

Brantley received an [[athletic scholarship]] to attend the University of Florida in [[Gainesville, Florida]], where he played for coach [[Doug Dickey]] and coach [[Charley Pell]]'s [[Florida Gators football]] teams from 1976 to 1979.  Brantley was a first-team All-[[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC) selection in 1977 and 1978 and received honorable mention [[All-American]] honors in 1977 and 1978.<ref name=2009ufmediaguidehistory>''2009 Florida Gators Football Media Guide'', [http://web.gatorzone.com/football/media/2009/pdf/143-172.pdf  History], University Athletic Association, Gainesville, Florida, pp. 143 & 152 (2009).  Retrieved July 1, 2010.</ref>  His senior season in 1979 was cut short by a brain injury after he was knocked unconscious in the Gators' first home game,<ref>Jack Hairston, "[http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Ru0cAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rGcEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6328,4866073&dq=scot-brantley&hl=en  Scot Brantley's Career Is Over]," ''Sarasota Herald-Tribune'', p. 1C (September 26, 1979).  Retrieved July 1, 2010.</ref> which was a severe blow to a team in the first year of a coaching transition.<ref>Norm Carlson, ''University of Florida Football Vault: The History of the Florida Gators'', Whitman Publishing, LLC, Atlanta, Georgia, p. 95 (2007).</ref>  Brantley led the Gators in [[tackle (football move)#American & Canadian football (gridiron football)|tackle]]s during the 1976 and 1978 seasons, and his career total of 467 tackles still ranks second on the Gators' all-time records list.<ref name=2009ufmediaguiderecords>''2009 Florida Gators Football Media Guide'', [http://web.gatorzone.com/football/media/2009/pdf/173-200.pdf  Records Book], University Athletic Association, Gainesville, Florida, pp. 187&ndash;188 (2009).  Retrieved July 1, 2010.</ref>

== Professional career ==

After his college career, the Tampa Bay Buccaneers selected Brantley in the third round (seventy-sixth pick overall) of the [[1980 NFL Draft]],<ref>Pro Football Hall of Fame, Draft History, [http://www.profootballhof.com/history/story.aspx?story_id=2014  1980 National Football League Draft].  Retrieved June 1, 2010.</ref> and he played linebacker for the Buccaneers for his entire eight-year NFL career from {{NFL Year|1980}} to {{NFL Year|1987}}.<ref name=nflprofile>National Football League, All-Time Players, [http://www.nfl.com/players/scotbrantley/profile?id=BRA643684  Scot Brantley].  Retrieved June 1, 2010.</ref>  Brantley became a regular starter in his third season in {{NFL Year|1982}}, played in 114 games and had eight [[interception]]s in his career.<ref name=pfbrprofile/>

== Life after the NFL ==

Following his professional football career, Brantley pursued a career in sports broadcasting.  He has served on the Gator Radio Network as both a color analyst during games and an analyst during pre-game, half-time and post-game shows.  Brantley also spent ten seasons as the broadcast partner of [[Gene Deckerhoff]] on the Buccaneers Radio Network.  He now hosts a daily radio show on [[WHBO]] in [[Tampa, Florida]] every weekday afternoon.<ref name=ginn6232006>Sharon Ginn, "[http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=8NMNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=UngDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5115,2341654&dq=scot-brantley&hl=en  Local radio brings aboard well-known voices]," ''St Petersburg Times'', p. 8C (June 23, 2006).  Retrieved July 1, 2010.</ref>

Brantley's broadcasting career has had ups and downs.  The Gators and Buccaneers both unexpectedly dropped him from their broadcast booths after the 2004 and 2005 seasons, respectively, after he had spent seven years in each of those positions.<ref name=english2262004>Antonya English, "[http://www.sptimes.com/2004/02/26/Sports/McGriff_replaces_Bran.shtml  McGriff replaces Brantley as UF color analyst]," ''St. Petersburg Times'' (February 26, 2004).  Retrieved July 1, 2010.</ref><ref name=korth5172006>Joanne Korth, "[http://www.sptimes.com/2006/05/17/Bucs/Nickerson_rejoins_Buc.shtml  Nickerson rejoins Bucs as color analyst]," ''St. Petersburg Times'' (May 17, 2006).  Retrieved July 1, 2010.</ref>  [[Hardy Nickerson]] replaced him for the Buccaneers broadcasts,<ref name=korth5172006/> while [[Lee McGriff]] took his spot when he returned to the Gators broadcasts after spending several years alongside [[Mick Hubert]] in the 1980s and 1990s.<ref name=english2262004/>  Brantley's previous radio show on WQYK-AM was also canceled due to format changes with the station.<ref name=ginn6232006/>

Brantley suffered two small [[stroke]]s in 2008, and lost most of his sight in his left eye as a result.<ref name=schwarz10082009>Alan Schwarz, "[http://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/09/sports/ncaafootball/09concussions.html  Ex-Gator's Concussion Sheds Light on Tebow's]," ''The New York Times'' (October 8, 2009).  Retrieved July 1, 2010.</ref>  He was forced to take a leave of absence from his radio broadcasting responsibilities while recovering from the strokes and subsequent heart surgery.<ref>Pat Dooley, "[http://www.gainesville.com/article/20090620/COLUMNISTS/906209910?Title=Gator-Nation-showing-support-for-Scot-Brantley  Gator Nation showing support for Scot Brantley]," ''The Gainesville Sun'' (June 20, 2009).  Retrieved July 1, 2010.</ref>

Brantley will be inducted into the Florida-Georgia Hall of Fame in October 2010.<ref>Gary Smits, "[http://jacksonville.com/sports/college/florida-gators/2010-06-10/story/florida-georgia-hall-fame-induct-four-players  Florida-Georgia Hall of Fame to induct four players]," ''Florida Times-Union'' (June 10, 2010).  Retrieved July 1, 2010.</ref>  He was previously inducted into the University of Florida Athletic Hall of Fame as a "Gator Great."<ref>F Club, Hall of Fame, [http://www.gatorfclub.org/hof/?p=greats  Gator Greats].  Retrieved July 1, 2010.</ref>

== Gator football family ==

Brantley's nephew, [[John Brantley|John Brantley, IV]], will be the Florida Gators' starting [[quarterback]] at the start of the fall 2010 college football season.<ref name=mahoney1252007>Jon Mahoney, "[http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/highschool/01/25/johnbrantley.profile/index.html  Gator genes: John Brantley will continue a great tradition at Florida]," ''Sports Illustrated'' (January 25, 2007).  Retrieved July 1, 2010.</ref>  His brother, John Brantley, III, was the Gators' starting quarterback in 1978.<ref name=mahoney1252007/>

